00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:46.070
The topic of biotech is
intriguing for many reasons.

00:02:46.070 --> 00:02:49.330
Since Stanford scientist
Herbert Boyer teamed up

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:53.340
with venture capitalist
Robert Swanson in 1976

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:55.920
to found the
Genentech Corporation,

00:02:55.920 --> 00:03:00.910
biotech has been at the nexus of
cutting-edge laboratory science

00:03:00.910 --> 00:03:02.970
and venture capital.

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:07.230
The commercialization of
recombinant DNA technology

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:10.300
has altered relationships
between universities,

00:03:10.300 --> 00:03:12.220
government, and industry.

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:14.380
In our daily lives,
it has changed

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:19.000
and will continue to change
in profound ways how we eat,

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
how we grow things,
and how we heal.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.420
Another reason that biotech
is an exciting field

00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:29.360
is that there are women
in leadership positions,

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:32.730
and there have been
from the very beginning.

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:36.420
When H. Stewart Parker
graduated from the University

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:41.250
of Washington in
1981, she was hired

00:03:41.250 --> 00:03:44.740
as the very first employee
of the Immunex Corporation

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:46.100
in Seattle.

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:50.290
From that start, she went on
to serve the biotech industry

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:54.360
as vice president of corporate
development, president, CEO,

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:57.300
director, chairman,
and lobbyist.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:03:59.980
Her career makes
the point that right

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:03.790
from the start of the
biotechnology industry, there

00:04:03.790 --> 00:04:06.400
have been women leading it.

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:09.290
I know that we have some of
them in the audience here today,

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:11.260
and we will hear from
others as we listen

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:13.450
to this afternoon's panels.

00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:16.670
But how many are there?

00:04:16.670 --> 00:04:22.940
In 2001, a study revealed
that women made up about 10%

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:27.010
of senior leadership
in top biotech firms.

00:04:27.010 --> 00:04:31.060
That study acknowledged that
the number was a little low.

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:34.470
But it also exuded
confidence that, with so many

00:04:34.470 --> 00:04:38.070
scientifically talented
women in the pipeline,

00:04:38.070 --> 00:04:41.300
those numbers were sure to soar.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:44.550
In some ways numbers
have climbed.

00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:49.010
More women than men now attend
college, more women than men

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:52.130
study biology at the
undergraduate and graduate

00:04:52.130 --> 00:04:57.030
levels, and more than half
of all biology PhDs today

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:59.640
are earned by women.

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:01.610
Women are not as
well represented

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:04.400
on science faculties
and universities,

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:07.000
but they make up an
increasing proportion

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.000
at the assistant rank.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:14.210
So 26% of biology
faculty at MIT are women.

00:05:14.210 --> 00:05:18.660
At Harvard, women constitute
30% of tenured and tenure

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:22.030
track biology professors
within the faculty of Arts

00:05:22.030 --> 00:05:24.060
and Sciences.

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:27.450
While all these changes have
been happening in academia,

00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:30.140
the practice of
science itself has

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:34.370
been altering in some other
quite significant ways.

00:05:34.370 --> 00:05:37.120
Most notably,
scientific research

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:41.340
has been increasingly
privatized and commercialized.

00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:45.570
What that means is that today's
most significant advances are

00:05:45.570 --> 00:05:49.840
just as likely to happen in
a privately owned lab geared

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:54.460
toward profit as they are
in a nonprofit, educational,

00:05:54.460 --> 00:05:56.840
or governmental setting.

00:05:56.840 --> 00:06:01.560
Corporate, particularly
venture capital sponsorship,

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:04.570
means that big
breakthroughs and big money

00:06:04.570 --> 00:06:08.730
are now very likely to be
made in the same place.

00:06:08.730 --> 00:06:11.780
So how many women
are in that place?

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:14.210
How have all the
optimistic predictions

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:17.600
made in 2001, that the
10% percent number was

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:20.760
about to take off, panned out?

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:24.260
Well, a study of
senior leadership

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:30.200
in top biotech firms in
2014 found that women

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:34.900
comprise-- are you ready-- 10%.

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:38.580
Where that 10% can be
found is also revealing.

00:06:38.580 --> 00:06:42.350
Massachusetts Biotech
Research Council data

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:46.570
showed that most senior
women are in communications,

00:06:46.570 --> 00:06:50.490
human resources, and
development-- important roles

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:55.330
to be sure, but still not
the same as directors,

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:59.250
chief financial officers,
or chief executives.

00:06:59.250 --> 00:07:02.020
Studies show that
the absence of women

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:06.080
does not arise from any lack
of ambition on women's parts,

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:07.560
and this is very important.

00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:11.120
In a 2014 survey of
industry leaders,

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:13.830
equal percentages
of men and women

00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:19.100
identified being named to
a board as a personal goal.

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:23.040
Yet, while 59% of
the men surveyed

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:27.930
had been invited to join a
board, only 16% of the women

00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:29.200
had.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:32.820
But don't worry, the
2014 study assures us.

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:35.700
There are so many talented
women in the pipeline

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:39.330
that the numbers are
about to skyrocket.

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:42.700
The numbers we're supposed
to do that in 2001.

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:45.080
But now, almost a
decade and a half

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:47.180
later, they still have not.

00:07:47.180 --> 00:07:52.160
So where are all those eagerly
awaited women in biotech?

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.290
Thanks to the work
of Nancy Hopkins,

00:07:54.290 --> 00:07:57.550
we have learned that they are
not on boards of directors

00:07:57.550 --> 00:08:00.160
or on scientific
advisory boards.

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:03.500
Hopkins used data from a
Kauffman Family Foundation

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:08.820
report to demonstrate that only
about 5% to 8% of those bodies

00:08:08.820 --> 00:08:10.960
consist of women.

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:15.290
So what is stopping up
this pipeline of women

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:18.170
in the biotech industry?

00:08:18.170 --> 00:08:23.110
One recent incident that got
a lot of press offers a clue.

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.450
Dr. Tim Hunt of the
UK holds a Nobel Prize

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:30.300
in physiology and medicine
for his work on cell division.

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:33.059
At the World Conference
of Science Journalists

00:08:33.059 --> 00:08:36.390
in South Korea this
past June, Dr. Hunt

00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:38.929
stated publicly that--
and I'm quoting him--

00:08:38.929 --> 00:08:42.447
"girls were nothing but
trouble in science."

00:08:42.447 --> 00:08:44.530
And here's what he said.
"Three things happen when

00:08:44.530 --> 00:08:46.550
they are in the lab.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:50.010
You fall in love with them,
they fall in love with you,

00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:52.810
and when you criticize
them they cry."

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:54.050
End quote.

00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:55.820
Well, that kind of
attitude could well

00:08:55.820 --> 00:08:59.600
be part of what is blocking
the promised pipeline.

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:01.650
Women facing
prejudice in science

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:05.200
is not a new topic, of
course, and concern about it

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:06.990
is not new either.

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:11.560
In 1994, the journal Science
ran a three-part series on women

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:12.900
in science.

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:16.480
At that time, editor-in-chief
Daniel E. Koshland reflected,

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:19.590
and I'm quoting him,
"Although many formal barriers

00:09:19.590 --> 00:09:22.870
to women's participation
in science have fallen,

00:09:22.870 --> 00:09:27.260
cultural attitudes and
antagonism remain."

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:30.320
Nobel Laureate Hunt certainly
proves that statement

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:31.360
to be true.

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:34.180
Koshland further wondered
more than 20 years ago

00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:36.470
in another quote,
"if society can

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:39.920
afford to be underutilize
the abilities of half

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:41.760
of its citizens."

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:44.090
More recently, a
team of researchers

00:09:44.090 --> 00:09:46.340
led by Laurel Smith-Doerr,
who's here with us

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:50.210
today, found that, and I
quote, "Women are currently,

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:53.550
and have historically
been, underrepresented

00:09:53.550 --> 00:09:59.450
in top leadership positions in
biotech policymaking, research,

00:09:59.450 --> 00:10:00.760
and management.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:03.540
Without equal input
from both men and women

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:09.440
in decision-making, solutions
to today's intractable problems

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:11.740
are unlikely to be optimal."

00:10:11.740 --> 00:10:13.650
Even more bluntly,
the study warned,

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:16.640
and I quote, "We are missing
out on talented leadership

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:18.270
and on diversity
in leadership that

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:20.360
could be readily achieved."

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:22.540
Missing out indeed.

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:25.990
A recent independent report
entitled "The Bottom Line--

00:10:25.990 --> 00:10:28.760
Corporate Performance and
Women's Representation

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:32.780
on Boards" found that
companies, including Fortune 500

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:36.420
companies, with three or
more women on their boards

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:40.840
outperformed their counterparts
with fewer women in all ways,

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:43.640
including financial success.

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:47.260
That evidence deserves
a wide hearing,

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:51.280
and it is likely that one of the
significant pressures keeping

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:55.950
women out of biotech boardrooms
is the dependence of startups

00:10:55.950 --> 00:11:00.680
on venture capitalists, who
may take risks in certain areas

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:05.180
but who are risk adverse in
others like gender equity.

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:10.620
Let's make sure that money
talks in this conversation.

00:11:10.620 --> 00:11:13.030
We seem, in conclusion,
to be facing

00:11:13.030 --> 00:11:16.130
a clear problem of
talent under-utilization

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:18.920
in the burgeoning
world of biotech.

00:11:18.920 --> 00:11:22.630
No field, no country,
no society can

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:26.780
afford to squander the talents
of half of its population.

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:29.020
Science certainly cannot.

00:11:29.020 --> 00:11:32.090
At Radcliffe, we have known
that to be true all the way back

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:34.130
to the days of Mary Bunting.

00:11:34.130 --> 00:11:36.670
So what better place
to ask questions

00:11:36.670 --> 00:11:41.540
about where women in biotech
have been, where they are now,

00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:45.450
and where we want them
to be in 10 years time?

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:49.650
I hope we will leave this room
today not only with a deeper

00:11:49.650 --> 00:11:53.480
understanding of the obstacles
to women's participation,

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:59.120
but also with new insight into
how we can turn things around.

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:02.300
To get our conversation started,
I'd now like to hand things

00:12:02.300 --> 00:12:04.650
over to Professor Dan Carpenter.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:08.180
Dan is the faculty director
of social science programs

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:11.640
at the Radcliffe Institute, and
he is also the Allie S. Freed

00:12:11.640 --> 00:12:15.440
Professor of Government in the
Faculty of Arts and Sciences.

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:16.697
So, Dan.

00:12:16.697 --> 00:12:20.106
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:29.780
-Thank you, Liz.

00:12:29.780 --> 00:12:34.700
I'm proud that Radcliffe today
hosts a conversation that

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:36.810
brings some of the best
and brightest minds

00:12:36.810 --> 00:12:40.020
from academia, industry,
and other domains

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:42.790
to talk about a critical
problem facing not only

00:12:42.790 --> 00:12:46.670
our system of science but also
our economy and one of its most

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:48.780
important industries.

00:12:48.780 --> 00:12:53.934
Dean Cohen has just outlined
the parameters of that problem,

00:12:53.934 --> 00:12:55.600
and you're going to
hear much, much more

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:57.590
in the hours that follow.

00:12:57.590 --> 00:12:59.570
We at Radcliffe
recognize, of course,

00:12:59.570 --> 00:13:03.380
that the gender gap in
biotech is a complex problem,

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:05.620
and that the facts on
the ground are changing

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:07.850
as we meet and speak today.

00:13:07.850 --> 00:13:10.200
Our panelists
indeed are also well

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:12.250
aware of the fluid
nature of this problem,

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:16.640
and of course of the enduring
structural disparities that

00:13:16.640 --> 00:13:20.800
continue to shape the
biotechnology industry.

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:25.840
The Radcliffe Institute excels
at the interdisciplinary.

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:28.920
There's a lot of talk
at various universities

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:31.820
about breaking out
of boxes, busting out

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:35.360
of silos, a lot of talk about
the importance of getting

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:36.280
interdisciplinary.

00:13:36.280 --> 00:13:38.820
But in my 20-year
experience in the academy,

00:13:38.820 --> 00:13:43.470
there is not a single place that
does it as well as Radcliffe.

00:13:43.470 --> 00:13:45.690
And that's the kind
of event that we're

00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:47.804
going to bring to you today.

00:13:47.804 --> 00:13:49.720
Some of the panelists
you will hear from today

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:52.260
are life scientists who
have had scientific training

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:56.400
and experiences in the life
sciences industry for decades.

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:58.600
The social science panelists
you will hear today

00:13:58.600 --> 00:14:01.880
are trained sociologists,
psychologists, and management

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:04.370
specialists, and
they have themselves

00:14:04.370 --> 00:14:07.500
spent decades studying
this industry in-depth

00:14:07.500 --> 00:14:09.476
and others like it.

00:14:09.476 --> 00:14:11.350
We're going to hear from
scientists, but also

00:14:11.350 --> 00:14:14.540
from those who study the
careers of scientists.

00:14:14.540 --> 00:14:17.610
We're going to hear from biotech
entrepreneurs, but also those

00:14:17.610 --> 00:14:22.180
who study, systematically
and with very granular data,

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:27.620
the operations and successes
or failures of biotech firms.

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:29.080
Before turning to
the first panel,

00:14:29.080 --> 00:14:32.540
let me transition
by way of a story.

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:34.980
I've written some on the
Food and Drug Administration

00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:39.390
and on food and drug law and
the regulations governing

00:14:39.390 --> 00:14:41.710
the pharmaceutical and
biotechnology industries,

00:14:41.710 --> 00:14:44.600
in a few years ago I had
the privilege of serving

00:14:44.600 --> 00:14:46.690
on the United States
Institute of Medicine,

00:14:46.690 --> 00:14:49.310
or IOM, committee
examining issues

00:14:49.310 --> 00:14:51.220
in the pharmaceutical industry.

00:14:51.220 --> 00:14:53.220
The report was commissioned
by the Food and Drug

00:14:53.220 --> 00:14:55.790
Administration,
which regulates all

00:14:55.790 --> 00:14:58.290
of the companies and the
people who invent and produce

00:14:58.290 --> 00:15:01.510
the products that together make
up the biotech world that we

00:15:01.510 --> 00:15:02.710
know.

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:05.850
When it came time to deliver
the report to the FDA,

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:08.770
my colleagues and I met with
the commissioner of the FDA

00:15:08.770 --> 00:15:11.580
and the top staff of the agency.

00:15:11.580 --> 00:15:14.940
On one side of the
table, the IOM committee.

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:16.990
On the other side, the FDA.

00:15:16.990 --> 00:15:21.240
Not in an adversarial setting,
but in one of deliberation

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:24.630
where the roles of each side
were clearly delineated.

00:15:24.630 --> 00:15:26.930
Here's what I
remember so clearly.

00:15:26.930 --> 00:15:31.460
Not a single person on the FDA
side of that table that day

00:15:31.460 --> 00:15:33.280
was a man.

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:36.000
Not just the commissioner,
Margaret Hamburg,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.590
but also the various
associate commissioners,

00:15:38.590 --> 00:15:42.830
the scientific staff, the
legal staff, and the others.

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:45.210
I wasn't the only
one who noticed this.

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:46.840
As one of my fellow
committee members--

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:49.930
there were several of them-- had
spent a lot of time at the FDA,

00:15:49.930 --> 00:15:54.480
he turned to be and said,
20 years ago, Dan, we

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:58.300
would have been sitting
across from a lineup of guys,

00:15:58.300 --> 00:16:02.770
and a much less stellar
crew than this one, at that.

00:16:02.770 --> 00:16:04.880
I'm not going to
name that gentleman,

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:07.070
but I think he was
probably right.

00:16:07.070 --> 00:16:08.140
Now keep in mind this.

00:16:08.140 --> 00:16:12.240
The business biotech model
rests and will continue to rest,

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:15.600
no matter what changes happen
under current legislation,

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:20.560
on company sponsors persuading
the FDA that their products are

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:22.490
safe and effective.

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:27.060
Quite beyond the important
ethical, social, and economic

00:16:27.060 --> 00:16:30.130
issues at stake today, there
is a business and management

00:16:30.130 --> 00:16:31.330
issue.

00:16:31.330 --> 00:16:33.260
Unless we think the
gender diversity

00:16:33.260 --> 00:16:36.400
has nothing to do with the
ability to make a case,

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:39.430
how sustainable a business
model, how sustainable

00:16:39.430 --> 00:16:42.240
an arrangement, is it
for an industry whose

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:44.730
higher echelons are
populated overwhelmingly

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:48.200
by men to make a
business life or death

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:51.040
case to an agency
increasingly staffed

00:16:51.040 --> 00:16:53.790
by the best and brightest women?

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:56.820
I'll leave that
for you to ponder.

