about what's going

00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:57.770
on at the very top of
biotech organizations.

00:23:57.770 --> 00:24:00.140
I'm going to start by talking
more about what's going on

00:24:00.140 --> 00:24:04.010
in the labs and how women have
more authority in certain kinds

00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:05.820
of lab settings than others.

00:24:05.820 --> 00:24:08.400
And then I'll get to the
question of the leadership

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:10.820
and founders of firms.

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:11.945
So here we go.

00:24:11.945 --> 00:24:14.700
Let's see if I can-- great.

00:24:14.700 --> 00:24:16.630
So I'm starting from
organizational theory,

00:24:16.630 --> 00:24:20.040
particularly from Woody Powell's
contribution, in which he

00:24:20.040 --> 00:24:23.500
contrasted forms of economic
organization, two of which

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:26.900
are network organizations
and hierarchies.

00:24:26.900 --> 00:24:29.470
So where hierarchy's main
mode of communication

00:24:29.470 --> 00:24:32.300
is routines in the network
form, communication

00:24:32.300 --> 00:24:34.390
happens through relationships.

00:24:34.390 --> 00:24:36.750
Conflict is resolved
in hierarchy

00:24:36.750 --> 00:24:40.670
more by rank and authority--
so boss says who wins.

00:24:40.670 --> 00:24:42.200
In the network
organizations, it's

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:44.930
more by reputation
and reciprocity.

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:47.510
And where hierarchy
has a more formal tone,

00:24:47.510 --> 00:24:49.910
network organizations
are more open-ended

00:24:49.910 --> 00:24:52.170
and tend toward
collective benefits

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:55.290
rather than following the rules
to move up the job ladder.

00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:59.150
And in the life sciences,
which is where I did my study,

00:24:59.150 --> 00:25:04.520
biotech firms that
work on human therapies

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:06.790
are how we measure
network organization--

00:25:06.790 --> 00:25:10.080
so the sort of small
entrepreneurial biotech firms--

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:12.070
in contrast to the
more hierarchical,

00:25:12.070 --> 00:25:15.170
large, multinational
pharmaceutical corporations

00:25:15.170 --> 00:25:19.600
and universities, which
are more hierarchical.

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:23.230
And so the question is, what
does that kind of variation

00:25:23.230 --> 00:25:25.780
mean for women in science?

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:27.700
And there are two
different kinds

00:25:27.700 --> 00:25:30.390
of hypotheses in the
social science literature,

00:25:30.390 --> 00:25:32.440
so it kind of goes both ways.

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:35.050
On the one hand,
there is research

00:25:35.050 --> 00:25:37.520
that says bureaucratic
rules are better

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:41.470
for combating discrimination--
so the threat of a lawsuit.

00:25:41.470 --> 00:25:43.290
And there's some
research, for example,

00:25:43.290 --> 00:25:45.910
on minorities in
the Army that shows

00:25:45.910 --> 00:25:48.100
that having a
bureaucratic structure

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:51.930
can actually be good
for racial integration

00:25:51.930 --> 00:25:53.560
in large bureaucracies.

00:25:53.560 --> 00:25:56.260
On the other hand, social
scientists like Kanter,

00:25:56.260 --> 00:25:58.620
who Monica just
mentioned, have long

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:01.040
noted informal organization
does not always

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:02.560
match the formal organization.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:05.340
So the larger the
bureaucracy, the larger

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:07.840
the shadow side that's cast.

00:26:07.840 --> 00:26:11.770
And that can make more room
for informal stereotypes

00:26:11.770 --> 00:26:13.770
and sort of the
old boy networks.

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:16.580
So here I was faced with this
literature that said, well,

00:26:16.580 --> 00:26:19.166
maybe on the one hand it's
better to have bureaucracy,

00:26:19.166 --> 00:26:20.790
and on the other hand
maybe it's better

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:23.450
to have these kind of
network organizations.

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:26.080
So of course, being
a good sociologist,

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:27.015
I turned to the data.

00:26:30.160 --> 00:26:33.570
So I'm going to talk a
little bit about some data

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:36.530
that I collected long ago,
which began my dissertation.

00:26:36.530 --> 00:26:39.350
