01:35:24.900 --> 01:35:29.490
is when you get past the
tipping point in organizations

01:35:29.490 --> 01:35:34.130
where there's not that
tiny minority of women.

01:35:34.130 --> 01:35:38.410
So when there's more of a
balance within organizations,

01:35:38.410 --> 01:35:41.500
you see that there's the
same spectrum of women

01:35:41.500 --> 01:35:43.790
as there are of men in
terms of their behavior.

01:35:43.790 --> 01:35:47.600
Sometimes somebody who's
outspoken and assertive

01:35:47.600 --> 01:35:50.610
is a bitch, excuse me.

01:35:50.610 --> 01:35:51.970
Others are not.

01:35:51.970 --> 01:35:53.470
And it's the same with men.

01:35:53.470 --> 01:35:56.180
Some of the assertive
behaviors are actually

01:35:56.180 --> 01:35:58.680
very productive and
functional, and some of them

01:35:58.680 --> 01:36:00.340
aren't in organizations.

01:36:00.340 --> 01:36:06.300
But you can only see that and
not get the one generalization

01:36:06.300 --> 01:36:09.690
when there's more of a balance.

01:36:09.690 --> 01:36:14.710
So finding a place, when
you're examining potentially

01:36:14.710 --> 01:36:17.100
a career in industry,
being in a place

01:36:17.100 --> 01:36:21.140
and actually observing
what is the gender balance.

01:36:21.140 --> 01:36:26.230
You're more likely to be able
to manifest those behaviors

01:36:26.230 --> 01:36:30.820
without as much backlash if
there is more gender balance

01:36:30.820 --> 01:36:32.480
within the organization.

01:36:32.480 --> 01:36:34.260
Just as a
top-of-my-head comment.

01:36:34.260 --> 01:36:35.340
-Thanks.

01:36:35.340 --> 01:36:37.190
Great.

01:36:37.190 --> 01:36:37.690
-Hi.

01:36:37.690 --> 01:36:38.898
My name is Renee [INAUDIBLE].

01:36:38.898 --> 01:36:41.080
I'm head of research
at a small biotech

01:36:41.080 --> 01:36:45.020
here in Cambridge that focuses
on biological data sciences.

01:36:45.020 --> 01:36:48.100
And this has been
very engaging and has

01:36:48.100 --> 01:36:51.850
gotten me thinking about the
constitution of the management

01:36:51.850 --> 01:36:55.130
team of my company over the last
10 years that I've been there.

01:36:55.130 --> 01:36:59.870
And it's gone from 0% women to
50% women, which is fantastic.

01:36:59.870 --> 01:37:01.580
I think it's a very
meritocracy-driven

01:37:01.580 --> 01:37:03.150
organization.

01:37:03.150 --> 01:37:06.260
There have been five women
on the management team.

01:37:06.260 --> 01:37:10.270
And one of the things that I
noticed was out of this five,

01:37:10.270 --> 01:37:12.850
four of us have come
up through the ranks.

01:37:12.850 --> 01:37:15.240
So we started at
entry-level positions.

01:37:15.240 --> 01:37:19.340
And my question is really, is
that a requirement for women

01:37:19.340 --> 01:37:20.530
in leadership positions?

01:37:20.530 --> 01:37:23.190
Must we demonstrate
our capabilities

01:37:23.190 --> 01:37:29.970
within the organization in
order to attain that level?

01:37:29.970 --> 01:37:32.330
-I'm trying to think
through very quickly

01:37:32.330 --> 01:37:35.420
my experience of the
women that I know that are

01:37:35.420 --> 01:37:38.040
in very senior positions.

01:37:38.040 --> 01:37:41.920
And I think there are a
predominance of them that

01:37:41.920 --> 01:37:44.170
have been with the
companies long time,

01:37:44.170 --> 01:37:48.850
but there are definitely more
in the last maybe five years

01:37:48.850 --> 01:37:52.260
that have been hired
in from the outside.

01:37:52.260 --> 01:37:58.270
So perhaps that's in my teeny,
tiny, insignificant data

01:37:58.270 --> 01:37:59.830
sample.

01:37:59.830 --> 01:38:02.580
There's a bit of a shift
that women can actually

01:38:02.580 --> 01:38:06.220
move now into those more
leadership positions.

01:38:06.220 --> 01:38:11.170
I actually did a study on this
same topic about 10 years ago.

01:38:11.170 --> 01:38:13.645
From our ranks, there were
hundreds of women there.

01:38:13.645 --> 01:38:15.625
And I led a study
because no women

01:38:15.625 --> 01:38:19.090
were getting promoted into group
leader positions from within.

01:38:19.090 --> 01:38:22.499
They were all being
hired from without.

01:38:22.499 --> 01:38:24.040
And we did a study,
both a perception

01:38:24.040 --> 01:38:27.010
study, only on one
company, and actually

01:38:27.010 --> 01:38:28.000
looking at the numbers.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:31.286
And the reasons turned out to be
that if you came into a company

01:38:31.286 --> 01:38:32.702
when you were early
in your career

01:38:32.702 --> 01:38:34.930
and you didn't display the
features that we needed,

01:38:34.930 --> 01:38:37.405
you were remembered
as that little girl.

01:38:37.405 --> 01:38:39.880
No matter you had
accomplished, the perception

01:38:39.880 --> 01:38:42.025
was you were still that
little girl that you

01:38:42.025 --> 01:38:44.087
came in as 10 years
ago, and you were never

01:38:44.087 --> 01:38:47.870
going to get promoted.

01:38:47.870 --> 01:38:50.646
so you were never going to
get promoted from within.

01:38:50.646 --> 01:38:52.020
And all of these
women were being

01:38:52.020 --> 01:38:54.490
hired from without
until we pointed it out.

01:38:54.490 --> 01:38:57.660
And leadership changed some of
their criteria for promotion

01:38:57.660 --> 01:39:01.560
and attempted to put in some
transparency and bureaucracy

01:39:01.560 --> 01:39:04.276
to allow women to be
promoted from within.

01:39:04.276 --> 01:39:07.100
And two women were then the year
later promoted to group leader.

01:39:07.100 --> 01:39:09.770
But we had to demand
it-- demand it.

01:39:09.770 --> 01:39:11.180
-Provide evidence.

01:39:11.180 --> 01:39:13.980
Yeah, great question.

01:39:13.980 --> 01:39:14.840
-Hi.

01:39:14.840 --> 01:39:17.770
